    {/* ── Design principles — the WHY ──────────────────────────────── */}
    <aside class="panel">
      <span class="panel-bracket panel-bracket-tl"></span>
      <span class="panel-bracket panel-bracket-tr"></span>
      <span class="panel-bracket panel-bracket-bl"></span>
      <span class="panel-bracket panel-bracket-br"></span>
 
      <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-zinc-500 mb-1">
        DESIGN PRINCIPLES
      </p>
      <h3 class="display text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-100 mb-4">
        Things that won't change
      </h3>
 
      <ul class="principles">
        <li>
          <span class="p-num">/01</span>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-zinc-100">Analyze then build.</strong>
            Rushing the process results in more mistakes. Make use of the proper debug techniques 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="p-num">/02</span>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-zinc-100">Stay close to the physics.</strong>
            I want to be both the person who knows why a circuit works and the one who knows
            twenty frameworks for connecting circuits.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="p-num">/03</span>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-zinc-100">Document everything.</strong>
            The work that isn't visible is the work that isn't useful. If I can't explain
            something clearly, I probably don't understand it well enough yet.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="p-num">/04</span>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-zinc-100">Teach what I'm learning.</strong>
            Tutoring isn't separate from research  it's the test of whether I
            actually understand the material.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
 
  </div>
